:"url";s:76:"https://i.pinimg.com/originals/ca/c5/20/cac52005208ff885ceaa679d73f26dd9.jpg";s:8:"filetype";s:4:"jpeg";s:5:"width";i:1024;s:6:"height";i:683;s:6:"source";s:48:"https://www.pinterest.com/pin/614811786604201493";s:6:"domain";s:17:"www.pinterest.com";}}s:7:"related";a:0:{}s:9:"sentences";a:51:{i:0;s:183:"Garden leave refers to the process where you spend part (or the full) duration of your notice period away from the office, on payroll and receiving contractual benefits of employment.";i:1;s:162:"Garden leave “garden leave” is the term given to a situation whereby an employee is required to serve out a period of notice at home (or “in the garden”).";i:2;s:58:"Once in effect, it often prevents the employee from being.";i:3;s:270:"The ultimate aim of garden leave is to keep the employee out of the marketplace for long enough to ensure that any information they have will go out of date, or for the employee's successor to establish themselves, particularly with customers, so as to protect goodwill.";i:4;s:73:"Garden leave clause implied even though no express contractual provision.";i:5;s:130:"Garden leave can also be instigated at the employee's request (if it suits you too) or as part of negotiated terms over departure.";i:6;s:25:"If you're still not sure.";i:7;s:170:"Garden leave is generally reserved for more senior employees who may have technological knowledge, strategic market and pricing information or valuable customer contacts.";i:8;s:160:"Garden leave is typically an arrangement where an employer requires an employee to stay away from work although the employment contract has not been terminated.";i:9;s:123:"Garden leave (or gardening leave) is when an employer tells an employee not to work for all or some of their notice period.";i:10;s:250:"‘“garden leave” is a colloquial or euphemistic term for an employer insisting that an employee, who has given notice, stay away from work for the duration of the notice period, whilst continuing to pay the employee’s remuneration’, at [84];";i:11;s:235:"Garden leave describes the practice whereby an employee leaving a job—having resigned or otherwise had their employment terminated—is instructed to stay away from work during the notice period, while still remaining on the payroll.";i:12;s:344:"Under uk law, it has always been possible (and remains advisable) to expressly provide in the contract that accrued holiday is to be taken during garden leave, or for the employer to give requisite notice to the employee to take it, but this decision suggests that the employer may simply have a right to count garden leave towards outstanding.";i:13;s:101:"It's a good idea to talk with your employer if there's any part of your redundancy notice you're not.";i:14;s:167:"In those jurisdictions, most employment relationships are governed by contract and can only be terminated by notice to the other party (and often only for cause by the";i:15;s:85:"To enjoy a garden leave provision allowing them to get paid even after leaving a job.";i:16;s:69:"They can ask you to take any unused holiday during your garden leave.";i:17;s:95:"An employer can’t ask an employee to go on garden leave unless you both agree (the agreement.";i:18;s:151:"In this short guide, we consider what exactly it is, what practical implications it may have for you, and what your rights are if you are placed on it.";i:19;s:191:"You must make sure either that the employee’s contract of employment gives you a specific and enforceable right to use garden leave or the employee agrees in advance, preferably in writing.";i:20;s:148:"Xperthr defines garden leave as the practice of requiring an employee not to attend their employer’s premises for work during their notice period.";i:21;s:176:"Moreover, during garden leave, the employer is under no obligation to provide work or assign any duties to the employee for the whole or part of the employee’s notice period.";i:22;s:51:"An employee is entitled and obliged to attend work.";i:23;s:113:"While this practice occurs in singapore, garden leave raises several unsettled legal issues under singapore […]";i:24;s:84:"This is used when an employee position is no longer needed during the notice period.";i:25;s:151:"Important employees are sometimes put on gardening leave so that they cannot give private information about their previous employer to a new employer :";i:26;s:303:"A garden leave clause should be included in every contract of employment and amongst other things it will strengthen the effectiveness of restrictive covenants.a garden leave clause requires an employee to stay away from the workplace and stop working even though their contract of employment continues.";i:27;s:64:"Instead, the employee is paid their full salary to stay at home.";i:28;s:150:"The aim of garden leave is to keep the employee out of the market place long enough for any information they have to go out of date, or to enable the.";i:29;s:132:"Gardening leave is a protectionist measure used by an employer when an employee is terminated or when they tender their resignation.";i:30;s:78:"{{#verifyerrors}} {{message}} {{/verifyerrors}} {{^verifyerrors}} {{#message}}";i:31;s:339:"Without prejudice to the provisions of clauses 4.3 (payment in lieu of notice) and 15.2 (summary dismissal), the company may, once notice of termination has been given by either side require the executive to cease performing his job for such period or periods of the notice period as the company shall in its absolute discretion determine.";i:32;s:135:"In the majority of occasions, employers should include a suitable provision in your contract of employment to allow you to be read more";i:33;s:91:"However, employers should be very careful using it if the employee wants to remain at work.";i:34;s:164:"In the clause, you can include details such as who they can communicate with regarding leave, what they should expect regarding attendance at the office, and so on.";i:35;s:130:"Gardening leave your employer may ask you not to come into work, or to work at home or another location during your notice period.";i:36;s:152:"Gardening leave is often used by employers wanting to protect themselves against competition or poaching of customers, clients, or staff by an employee.";i:37;s:245:"Garden leave describes the practice whereby an employee who is leaving a job (having resigned or otherwise had his or her employment terminated) is instructed to stay away from work during the notice period, while still remaining on the payroll.";i:38;s:116:"Garden leave is a notice period where employees are restricted from working but they still get a normal rate of pay.";i:39;s:153:"The right to place an employee on garden leave is a contractual one, meaning you should include a garden leave clause when drafting an employee contract.";i:40;s:158:"The meaning of garden leave (often known as ‘gardening leave’), is that you require the employee to be away from the workplace during their notice period.";i:41;s:96:"It can only be enforced on you once you have resigned with notice or been dismissed with notice.";i:42;s:131:"If your employer says you do not have to be at work (known as 'garden leave') you must get paid as usual during your notice period.";i:43;s:291:"A clause to be inserted into an employment contract (for example, standard documents, employment contract for a junior employee or employment contract for a senior employee) or separate agreement giving the employer the right to require the employee to stay at home during the notice period.";i:44;s:37:"This is called ‘gardening leave’.";i:45;s:146:"This could be because the employer does not want the employee to have access to sensitive or confidential information they could use in a new job.";i:46;s:170:"(also garden leave) in the uk, a period of time after an employee leaves a job when they continue to be paid but are neither allowed to go to work nor to begin a new job.";i:47;s:186:"During this period the employee continues to receive all salary and benefits but is prohibited from commencing employment with new employers until the gardening leave period has expired.";i:48;s:106:"Garden leave can be useful when both the employee and employer agree to its use in a particular situation.";i:49;s:169:"Boston (ap) — whether or not they choose to spend their idle time in their yards, workers with noncompete contracts in massachusetts will soon be the first in the u.s.";i:50;s:173:"Suspension from work on full pay during a notice period, typically to prevent an employee from influencing the organization or acting to benefit a competitor before leaving.";}}